(9979, 1788, 'movie_plot', 'The Taste of Tea chronicles the eccentric Haruno family in their seemingly trivial everyday ambitions - Yoshiko, the family matriarch, is looking to revive her career as an animator, while her husband conducts his business as a hypnotherapist. Their teenage son, Hajime, has his hands full conquering the first stings of love, while Sachiko, the little sister, deals with her own problems in the form of a giant-sized doppelganger. Topping the dysfunction off are an oddball Grandpa who seems to be living on another planet, and a wayward uncle looking to confront his feelings to an ex-lover, played nonchalantly by the great Asano Tadanobu as always.\r\n\r\nAs the summer sun hangs high and the days remain lazy, each tale of personal triumph unfolds in a manner only director Katsuhito Ishii can envision, with striking visuals, toilet humor, wacky song and dance numbers and all. But beneath all the quirky non sequitur and surreal metaphors, the film offers a quintessential Japanese wisdom by celebrating the small marvels and joys of life.\r\n\r\n(Japanese with English subtitles)'),
